text:
Hey Linda, please meet Riley your incredible E-Mentor we've been telling you about :smile:. Feel free to introduce yourselves, say a little bit about what you would like to get out of the mentorship and continue chatting within this channel. :wave:

I will now be leaving the channel, but please direct message myself or penny-prospela if you have any questions. All the best for now! :slightly_smiling_face:

Note: You will not see your match as a "member" in this channel however you can see from the chat history that they have joined/been added :smile:

Hey Riley! I'm Linda and I'm now a 3D look dev artist based in NYC. I just graduated last year from School of Visual Arts, MFA CA. I mainly focus on texturing and shading but can also do lighting and modeling!
I hope I could get some help in finding job and something about freelance jobs (btw I was an internship ar Hornet Studio from last year Sep to this year Jan)

Hey Linda! Great to meet you. I'm Riley and I model, texture, and lookdev at Framestore NY. It seems like you are on a really good track with what you are interested in. Being able to model, texture, lookdev, and light is good for the New York market, because generally studios are hiring for more generalist roles. Yet it's also good to have a core skill you are really good at. SVA is a great school,cand congrats!
Cool I would be happy to answer any questions about freelance or staff roles. Nice, so you've got some production experience. Do you have a demo reel?
Nice to meet you! Now I don have any job and worried about that. Wait a minute lemme show you

attachments.title: Kroger - Zero Hunger | Zero Waste
attachments.text:
The Zero Hunger | Zero Waste initiative is Kroger’s social impact plan designed to cut down on food waste and commit to ending hunger by the year 2025. To spread the word about the cause, Kroger and DDB New York turned to Hornet director César Pelizer to create a spot that would be a little different from the bubbly, feel-good anthem and holiday spots, and instead, offer an emotional and symbolic story about unity and inclusion—something sweet and simple, with both clarity and emotional resonance, that would tackle the disturbing fact that one in nine Americans struggle with hunger. With diverse, expressive characters and a subtle narrative about eight people seated around a table offering a ninth seat to a lonely person walking by, César created an inclusive spot with a powerful and uplifting message.
